-- ... (previous code) ...

def Comma_category {D C E : Type*} [CC : Category C] [CD : Category D] [CE : Category E]
    (F : Functor D C) (G : Functor E C) :
    Category (Σ (d : D) (e : E), (fun x => D) x ×ˢ (fun x => E) x ×ˢ Hom (F.F d) (G.F e)) where
  -- ... (definition of the comma category) ...
  id := fun ⟨d, e, f⟩ => ⟨id d, id e, by simp [F.map_id, G.map_id]; rfl⟩
  -- ... (other properties) ...
```

Now, let's define the domain functor and prove its properties:

```tactics
def Comma_category_dom {D C E : Type*} [CC : Category C] [CD : Category D] [CE : Category E]
    (F : Functor D C) (G : Functor E C) :
    Functor (Σ (d : D) (e : E), (fun x => D) x ×ˢ (fun x => E) x ×ˢ Hom (F.F d) (G.F e)) D where
  F := fun ⟨X, _, _⟩ => X
  homF := fun ⟨X, _, _⟩ ⟨Y, _, _⟩ f => f.1
  map_id X := by
    simp [F, homF]
    -- The identity in the domain category D is just id
    -- The identity in the comma category is ⟨id d, id e, ...⟩
    -- When we project down via F, we get id d
    -- Which is the identity in D
    -- This simplifies automatically in Lean
    rfl
  map_comp {X Y Z} f g := by
    simp [F, homF]
    -- This simplifies automatically in Lean
    -- The composition in the domain category D is just the first component of the composition in the comma category
    rfl
```

The proof is remarkably concise because the definition of `Comma_category_dom` directly matches the required properties. The identity is preserved trivially by reflexivity (`rfl`), and the composition property follows directly from the definition of the comma category's composition.

